ponding to the diversity among Christian groups of which some later came to be perceived as heretical. Remains of art, architecture and texts from these contexts were discussed in two conferences gathering scholars who are excellent within their respective fields: text studies, studies of rites, archaeology, architecture, history of art, and cultural anthropology. These different fields of research have in recent years generated new knowledge that is relevant for the discussion of ablution and initiation rites and their function in late antiquity. At the same time interests of research have altered in favour of a growing cooperation across discipline borders.The present volumes are the outcome of two conferences in Rome 2008 and at Metochi (Lesbos) 2009.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aInitiation. 4aRitus. 4aTaufe. 4aWaschung. 7aRELIGION / Christian Rituals & Practice / General.2bisacsh  aAblution.  aBaptism.  aInitiation.  aRite.1 aAasgaard, Reidar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aApostolos-Cappadona, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssmann, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Eve-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetz, Hans Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlomkvist, Vemund, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandt, Olof, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrändle, Rudolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, J. Patout, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByrskog, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb